ccess_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSocial Policy Review provides students, academics and all those interested in welfare issues with detailed analyses of progress and change in areas of major interest during the past year. Bringing together a selection of commissioned papers, the Review is organised in three parts. First, it concentrates on the main policy developments during 2005 in relation to five key areas of welfare provision, both in the UK and internationally. The second part, this year concentrating on the theme of health and well-being, draws on current research to explore key policy issues and challenges. The final section explores employment and later life - an often neglected area of social policy, yet one that will increasingly dominate the contemporary news agenda and that has long term implications for social policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aPublic welfarezGreat Britain. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Policy.2bisacsh1 aAinscow, Mel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBauld, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBauld, Linda, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBurchardt, Tania, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCameron, Elaine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarke, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarke, Karen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCraig, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCummins, Robert A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDornan, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDyson, Alan, econtributo